{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-05505/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-05505"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:55:05"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["plan américain"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["high"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, handheld"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["two shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman rolls over a woman passed out on a hotel bed."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-05505","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-05505"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1/590ed3f6-c467-4598-9d3c-87c31edbd051","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T14:00:35.981Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Journalist Kyle Buchanan pointed out to PTA the parallel between what Reynolds and Alma do in this scene to get the dress back from Barbara Rose and the behind-the-scenes struggles PTA faced during the production of his first film, <em>Hard Eight</em>. His response: “A very good friend of mine said that to me the other day as well, and I had not in any way consciously thought of that. I certainly see those parallels, and I certainly have those feelings of pride and ego and protection about something I’ve made, where you want to see it go out into the world and be treated properly. You can be an artist while you’re making these things, but once they leave that showroom, they’re not yours anymore. That’s where the designer Charles James came into it: I thought about how obsessive he would be, that he would get garments back and then continue working on them” (Buchanan, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW114189148 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.vulture.com/2017/12/director-paul-thomas-anderson-on-phantom-thread-mortality.html\"><u>Love, Death, and Control</u></a>”).</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05505/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:30.326791140140017,27.219877130760324,253.4690366972477,224.27608944954127"}}}]}]}]}